Definition 2.2. Let $A,B$ be two objects of $\mathbb{C}$. A map $f\colon A\to B$ is called a morphism of $\mathbb{C}$ if it satisfies: $\displaystyle f(a+a^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=f(a)+f(a^{\prime}),$ $\displaystyle f(a\ast a^{\prime})$ $\displaystyle=f(a)\ast f(a^{\prime}),$ for all $a,a^{\prime}\in A$, $\ast\in\Omega_{2}^{\prime}$ and also commutes with all $w\in\Omega_{1}^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $\pi\colon M\to B$ be an epimorphism. We call Galois groupoid of $\pi$ to the groupoid ${\mathcal{G}al}_{\pi}=M\times_{B}M\rightrightarrows M$ where the target and source morphisms are the natural projections $\pi_{1}$ and $\pi_{2}$ respectively.
Definition 4.1. A Picard-Vessiot ring for the system (1) is a $\Delta$-ring extension $\mathcal{K}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{L}$ such that: (a) $\mathcal{L}$ is $\Delta$-simple, i.e. it does not contain non-trivial $\Delta$-ideals. (b) $\mathcal{L}=\mathcal{K}\{\Phi,\Phi^{-1}\}$ for some fundamental matrix $\Phi\in{\rm GL}(\mathcal{L})$ of solutions of (1). A $\Delta$-ring extension $i\colon\mathcal{K}\hookrightarrow\mathcal{L}$ is a Picard-Vessiot ring extension if it is a Picard-Vessiot ring extension for some linear differential system with coefficients in $\mathcal{K}$. The quotient field of a Picard-Vessiot ring extension is called a Picard-Vessiot field extension.
Definition 2.5. We say that an epimorphism $\pi\colon M\to B$ of ${\bf Cat}$ is $\ldots$ (a) $\ldots$ weakly Galois if it admits a Galois structure. (b) $\ldots$ strongly Galois if it is weakly Galois and it satisfies the additional conditions: (i) It is normal. (ii) It admits a unique (up to isomorphism) strong Galois structure. We call Galois group of $\pi$ to the group object ${\rm Gal}_{\pi}$ appearing in the unique strong Galois structure.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{G}\rightrightarrows M$ be a grupoid object and $\alpha\colon G\times M\to M$ an action of a group object in a category $\bf Cat$. A grupoid isomorphism $G\ltimes M\xrightarrow{\sim}\mathcal{G}$ is called a split. In such case, we say that the groupoid object $\mathcal{G}$ splits in ${\bf Cat}$, $G$ is a splitting group, and $\alpha$ is a splitting action for $\mathcal{G}$ in ${\bf Cat}.$
Definition 2.4. Let $\pi\colon M\to B$ be an epimorphism in $\bf Cat$. A Galois structure for $\pi$ is an splitting action $\alpha\colon G\times M\to M$ for $\mathcal{G}al_{\pi}$. We say that a Galois structure is strong in Cat if the action $\alpha$ induces an isomorphism $G(\{\star\})\xrightarrow{\sim}{\rm Aut}_{B}(M)$.
Definition 2.2. We say that $\pi$ is normal if for any object $Z$ in Cat we have ${\rm Hom}(M,Z)^{{\rm Aut}_{B}(M)}={\rm Hom}(B,Z)$.
Definition 2.1. A Petri net $N$ is a 4-tuple $(P_{N},T_{N},{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N},{(-)^{\circ}}_{N})$, where: • $P_{N}$ is a set, called the set of places; • $T_{N}$ is a set, called the set of transitions; • ${{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N},{(-)^{\circ}}_{N}$ are functions $T_{N}\to\mathcal{M}^{\mathbb{N}}_{P_{N}}$, called input and output, respectively. A state for the net $N$ is an element of $\mathcal{M}^{\mathbb{N}}_{P_{N}}$, representing how many tokens are in each place. Given nets $N:=(P_{N},T_{N},{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N},{(-)^{\circ}}_{N})$ and $M:=(P_{M},T_{M},{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{M},{(-)^{\circ}}_{M})$, a morphism from $N$ to $M$ is a pair $\langle f,g\rangle$ where $f$ is a function $T_{N}\to T_{M}$, $g$ is a monoid homomorphism $\mathcal{M}^{\mathbb{N}}_{P_{N}}\to\mathcal{M}^{\mathbb{N}}_{P_{M}}$, and the following conditions hold: $f;{{}^{\circ}}(-)_{M}={{}^{\circ}}(-)_{N};g\qquad f;{(-)^{\circ}}_{M}={(-)^{% \circ}}_{N};g$ It is straightforward to check that Petri nets and Petri net morphisms form a category, called $\textbf{Petri}^{\mathbb{N}}$.
